          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Bograth and Paradwyn Magi for beginners<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9510'>Haris "Shockwaver" Kopic</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9510&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 19, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Bograth:<br>
<br>
Aaaaah, it arrived at last.....the mighty swamp region. Their specialization is strength in numbers, and most of the magi support that fact.<br>
<br>
The set-up I am currently working with is Golthub-Grahnna-Brog.<br>
For those of you who don&#39;t know those guys, ill list them below:<br>
<br>
Golthub:<br>
17/4--Starting: Glablit, Gremble, Moob<br>
Power-Mire: Choose any one region. Defeat Golthub. Discard all non-magi cards of the chosen region from play.<br>
Golthub can only play Bograt, Core, and Universal cards.<br>
<br>
Grahnna:<br>
13/4--Starting: Mirago, Treepsh, Trulb<br>
Effect-Share: Whenver you play a Bograth creature, choose any one Bograth creature in play. Add one energy to the chosen creature.<br>
Effect-Transform: When you reveal Grahnna, if your previous magi was Wiep, place any one Bograth card from your discard pile into your hand.<br>
<br>
Brog:<br>
14/5--Starting: N&#39;Kala, Gwaeg, Zungg<br>
Effect-Fertilize: Whenever a creature is discarded from play in an attack, add one energy to Brog.<br>
<br>
And if you want to know their starting cards, check out Magi-Nation.com, they&#39;ve completed their ND preview section by now. They&#39;re pretty irrelevant now anyways.<br>
Ok, here it goes. Generally, with Golthub, you want to go second. Because of his power, if the opponent spends all his magi&#39;s starting energy, you can just use Mire to defeat all his cards and thus his magi if he has no energy left on him. Other than that, if the opponent holds back with the energy, just start setting up your army of weenies and try to overrun him with the usual Bograth strategy: srength in numbers. Should you be forced down to Grahnna, (which you usually will), go all out with your creatures. Each new one you play will make one of the ones you have in the game stronger. Her Transform effect can be quite nice as well, bringing back some useful cards but it doesn&#39;t apply to this deck so don&#39;t worry about that now. Grahnna is a very good magi to use for a huge swarm, because of her lovely lovely Share effect, each new creature you play strengthens another one already in play. If Grahnna is defeated, Brog gets behind the wheel. His effect is pretty cool, considering there&#39;s no limit to the number of times it&#39;s triggered each turn. And since generally creatures die in combat, you will almost always have enough energy to put down new creatures on your next turn. This was a pretty general strategy section, if you have any questions, feel free to drop me a line.<br>
<br>
On to the jungle dwellers, the race of magi which inhabit the Paradwyn region, a tropical jungle in the moonlands.<br>
<br>
I am not very familiar with this region yet, but I will try to provide a good usable strategy for magi nevertheless. <br>
<br>
Iain-Yricho-Ninx<br>
<br>
Iain:<br>
12/5--Starting: T&#39;Kanzam, Ambush<br>
Effect-Beginning&#39;s End-4: Choose any one opposing creature in play.  Discard energy from that creature equal to its starting energy.<br>
<br>
Yricho:<br>
16/5--Starting: Mydra, Poison Baloo Root, Yricho&#39;s Staff.<br>
Effect-Athletic: Once per turn, immediately after an opposing player uses a power on his or her cards, you can use a power on one of your cards in play.<br>
<br>
Ninx:<br>
12/6--Starting: Blade Hyren, Pagajack, Weave Mat.<br>
Power-Stare Down: Choose any one opposing magi in play with more energy than Ninx.  The chosen Magi&#39;s energy becomes equal to the energy on Ninx.<br>
<br>
Ok, here it goes. Iain is evil. Period. His power is just awesome, and it is very useful in almost any situation in the game. Imagine your opponent&#39;s reaction after you kill his Rock Hyren, which he bitterly had to save energy for, for only 4 energy. If the creature has less energy than it&#39;s starting it dies, if it has its starting energy, it dies. If it has more, it is siginificantly weakened. But be careful though, don&#39;t use his power every turn. Remember to play creatures too, or else you won&#39;t be able to finish off your opponent. When Iain dies, Yricho is there to replace him. His effect is just plain fun. And if your opponent has a Magi such as Tryn or Grega, he will typically use his power every turn, allowing you to use one of your card&#39;s powers effectively twice each turn. If combined with cards such as Ookami&#39;s Drums, this can be very useful and fun to use.  It&#39;s a good thing.  And last, but sure as he!! not least, Ninx is one evil sister. Her power can be very fun and satisfying to use against decks that have tons of energy on their magi like Kazm or the Dark Twins. She also has cool starting cards and an above average energize, which makes her very compatible for the last turn, since 6 E every tun will usually allow you to play at least 1 creature to reinforce your army.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
This is it. My opinion on the Magi of the 2 new regions. Very newbie friendly again. If there are any questions about further and more in-depth strategy about either region, feel free to D or E mail me and I will answer your questions to the best of my ability.<br>
<br>
I hope you enjyed this article and/or got some help from it.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
